\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\strike\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\tx5400\aspalpha 75.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 In the upstream market Anglo has a market share of 28% (it owns the Black Mountain mine), Kumba 36% (it owns the Rosh Pinah mine), BHP Billiton 11% (it owns the Pering mine), Metorex 12% (it owns the Maranda mine) and imports 17%. Post the merger Anglo wil
l have a market share of 64% in the upstream zinc market. However, both the Pering and the Maranda mine will stop producing by 2004. Black Mountain is expected to close in 2013 and Rosh Pinah has 8 years of production left. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\lang2057\fs24\qj\tx5400\aspalpha 76.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang2057\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f4\loch\f4 Zinc concentrate is not traded on the London Metal Exchange (\'93LME\'94) because all of the zinc concentrate produced in South Africa is supplied to Zincor. It is sold by way of long-term contracts between the mine and smelter.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 For historical reasons mines are paid for only 85% of the zinc in concentrate. This has persisted even though smelters now recover 95% of the zinc in the concentrate. The difference between the 85% paid for and the 95% recovered is referred to as \'93free zi
nc\'94. The zinc that is paid for is called \'93payable zinc\'94. The mine pays the smelter a fee known as the treatment charge to transform the concentrate into saleable zinc metal. The treatment charge is set in annual negotiations with reference to a base price,
 normally an expected SHG price. The treatment charge is typically about 40% of the actual SHG price.}}}
{\*\cs205\cf0{\*\updnprop5800}\up6\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4 }{\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4  The price is, however, tied to t
he LME benchmark price for Special High Grade zinc (\'93SHG\'94). The lack of exports of zinc concentrate from Southern Africa is an indication that the prices paid by Zincor for zinc concentrate have been sufficiently high to make it more economic for independe
nt producers of zinc concentrate to supply Zincor than to sell their product on the export market. We therefore regard the geographic market as international.    }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\lang2057\fs24\qj\tx5400\aspalpha 77.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang2057\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f4\loch\f4 In the downstream market the zinc refinery, in this case Zincor, receives concentrated ore from the various mines and refines it into one of the primary grades of zinc metal.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Zincor is regarded as the 3{{\*\updnprop5800}\up5 rd} lowest cost producer of zinc metal in the western world, according to international benchmarking by Brook Hunt 2000.}}}
{\*\cs205\cf0{\*\updnprop5800}\up6\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4 }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\tx5400\aspalpha 78.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\tx5400{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 The local input of zinc concentrate is insufficient to meet Zincor\'92s demand. Zincor, therefore, imports 4% of its concentrate requirements. It receives 24% of its zinc concentrate from Rosh Pinah, 36% from Black Mountain, 12% from Maranda and 20% from Peri
ng.   \tab }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 79.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 Nearly all of the output of the Zincor refinery, 87%, is used within South Africa and 13% is exported. The majority of its output, around 24%, is sold to Iscor, its largest customer, and 63% to other domestic customers. Its zinc customers are all located w
ithin a 100km radius of its plant, located near Johannesburg. Approximately 10% of domestic consumption is imported, mostly by customers located close to the coast in Cape Town. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi60\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\lang2057\fs24\qj\aspalpha 80.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang2057\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f4\loch\f4 Zinc metal is an internationally traded commodity and is traded on the LME. The price paid for zinc metal in South Africa equals the LME price plus a premium that is individually negotiated between buyers and sellers to reflect the quality of the zinc purc
hased and logistical issues.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Transport only represents 2% of total cost. Thus if the local price is raised by 5%, customers will turn to imports.}}}
{\*\cs205\cf0{\*\updnprop5800}\up6\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4 }{\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4  It is priced at near import parity.}{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af1\afs20\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs20\lang2057\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Dr Hilmar Rode of Anglo, told the Tribunal that Zincor indicates on its website that it purchased zinc concentrate on international terms, see transcript p. 297. }}}
{\*\cs205\cf0{\*\updnprop5800}\up6\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4 }{\rtlch\af4\ltrch\dbch\af4\hich\f4\loch\f4  We thus regard the geographical market as international.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 81.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 According to the IDC the transaction will have a horizontal effect on the zinc market leading to the diminishing or prevention of future competition in the zinc market.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 82.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 Zincor, operated by Kumba, is the only zinc refinery that is operating in the downstream market. According to the IDC there are, from an anti-trust perspective, two possible future entrants that could come into the market and compete with Zincor. The first
 is Anglo\'92s Gamsberg project, not yet established, but which in terms of its proposal would have included a refinery, and the second, the Skorpion refinery in Namibia, also being developed by Anglo. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 83.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s16\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 The Gamsberg project was, according to Mr Trahar, mothballed indefinitely in 2001 because of a depressed zinc market and the Skorpion refinery in Namibia is prohibited from selling into the Customs Union Area because it is part of an Export Processing Zone
. Anglo, therefore, argues that these two refineries could not be regarded as potential entrants.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 84.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 However, should the Gamsberg project be reactivated it would, according to Anglo, not affect prices in the zinc market. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 85.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s17\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 The IDC argues that the coincidence between the decision to mothball the Gamsberg project and the date at which Anglo must have considered acquiring its interest in Kumba could lead one to draw the inference that the only reason the project was abandoned w
as because with the merger, Anglo had no need to own its own refinery. The explanation that Anglo would never have entered because of the present state of the market is not credible, according to the IDC. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s17\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\cf2\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 86.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s17\cf2\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{ Anglo vehemently deny this and state that the Gamsberg project would not have happened in the present state of the zinc market even absent the merger.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Given its location in the Western Cape, well away from the bulk of the domestic customer base for zinc metal which is inland, the project needed to be largely dependent on exports to be viable.}}}
{\*\cs205\cf0{\*\updnprop5800}\up6\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 }{ Whilst we are in no position to resolve this dispute of fact we need not do so. The evidence turns on wh
ether, if Gamsberg had come on line as a refinery, it would have led to a substantial reduction of zinc metal prices for domestic consumers.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 87.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s16\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 The zinc metal pricing is pinned somewhere between export and import parity. According to Anglo the Johannesburg PWV area is the largest zinc metal market and the difference between import and export parity pricing is of the order of 2-3%. In terms of the 
two import satellite markets being Cape Town and Durban, the difference in export and import parity pricing is 1% and less. These percentages will thus be the maximum potential reduction in pricing, should Gamsberg enter the market. Firms involved in galva
nising, who are the most important downstream consumers of zinc metal, indicated to Anglo that zinc represents 20% of their costs. Thus the reduction of 2-3% of a 20% cost input is very small and will thus not have a substantial effect on competition. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\cf2\f4\lang2057\f4\fs24\f4\qj\aspalpha 88.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s17\cf2\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe1033\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{ The evidence of Anglo,s Dr Rode, who was the only witness on this point which was not disputed by the IDC, was that the price reduction if Gamsberg had been on line would have been felt in Gauteng only, but that nevertheless even this fact was uncertain as
 Gamsberg, given its location, is not favourably situated to supply Gauteng.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Transport cost from a South African port to Johannesburg by truck represents approximately 2% of the zinc price.}}}
{\*\cs205\cf0{\*\updnprop5800}\up6\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang1033\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe1033\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 }{ }}
